Jeff the Finn <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://webpages.charter.net/nilus" target="top"><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://webpages.charter.net/nilus/nban44.JPG" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#F5F5DC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bsparrowshearth.showUserPublicProfile?gid=eugene210>Eugene210</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered Member</span><br>  Posts: 26<br> <font color=#B87333>(6/27/03 9:18 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fsparrowshearthfrm7.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=19.topic&index=28>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Eucharist</span><hr size=1> Jeff the Finn:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Yes the New Testament evolved, and before any writing became Scripture it was tested and approved by usage. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
We seem to have a disagreement on the meaning of &quot;Scripture&quot;.  I believe it is inherently authoritative, and was invested with such authority as the ink dried on the page.<br>
<br>
Church councils simply recognized what was already witnessed by the Spirit.  And so, the fact that an early church father is a witness to canonicity does not render his interpretations binding.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>2 Peter 3:15-16 (NIV)<br>
